Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in stylistic natural language generation—particularly with literary devices like similes—is not merely generating a semantically appropriate comparison, but determining *where* such a device should be inserted to preserve or enhance the flow of meaning. While Papers 1–3 focus on prompt optimization via gradient-inspired search, regularization, and constrained generation, they treat prompts as functional tools for task performance rather than expressive elements shaping narrative texture. My idea diverges by reframing simile insertion as a *contextual perturbation minimization problem*, where the goal is not just coherence but minimal disruption (or maximal enhancement) of the latent semantic trajectory of a text. I integrate reinforcement learning (RL) to model placement decisions as sequential actions, using contextual embeddings to quantify perturbations caused by insertion. Unlike prior work that optimizes prompts for accuracy or zero-shot transfer, this approach targets aesthetic and cognitive fluency—measuring how well a simile "fits" without derailing context. The novelty lies in combining perturbation sensitivity analysis with policy-based RL, training an agent to identify insertion points where the KL-divergence between pre- and post-insertion context distributions is minimized, while maximizing human-perceived stylistic value. This bridges computational linguistics with cognitive models of reading comprehension, offering a new paradigm for machine-assisted creative writing.

